It's true that light travels much faster than sound waves - about 874,030 times faster in air at room temperature. That's why we see lightning before hearing the thunder during a storm. The light from the lightning strikes our eyes almost instantly, while it takes several seconds for the sound of the thunderclap to reach our ears.

Applying that concept figuratively to people appearing "bright" (intelligent) before you hear them speak (and realize they aren't so smart after all) is really funny and insightful. Appearances can definitely be deceiving!
